{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.02,0.11,0.7,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43711"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3542"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of painful neck swelling. The pain radiates to her jaw and she has difficulty swallowing. She was diagnosed with influenza two weeks ago but has otherwise recovered. She has no significant medical history apart from an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery 12 months ago. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy. Her tonsils and pharynx appear normal and cranial nerve examination is unremarkable. The anterior neck lump is tender to palpation with a soft swelling that moves upward on swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical lymphadenopathy","Influenza A infection","Postpartum thyroiditis","Subacute thyroiditis","Autoimmune thyroiditis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Esubacute thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as de Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis or granulomatous thyroiditis. The temporal relationship with a recent viral infection (typically 2-8 weeks prior), painful thyroid swelling that moves with swallowing, and radiation of pain to the jaw are characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not explain the thyroid tenderness or movement of the mass with swallowing. While mild lymphadenopathy is present, it is likely reactive to the thyroid inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfluenza A infection\u003C/strong\u003E has resolved in this patient. While it was likely the trigger for the thyroiditis, the current symptoms represent a post-viral inflammatory process rather than active infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostpartum thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs 2-6 months after delivery, not at 12 months. It is also typically painless and may present with symptoms of thyroid dysfunction rather than local pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E (Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis) is typically painless and presents with gradual onset of hypothyroid symptoms rather than acute neck pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe natural history of subacute thyroiditis typically follows three phases over 6-12 months: initial hyperthyroidism due to follicular destruction and thyroid hormone release, followed by hypothyroidism, and finally return to normal thyroid function. Treatment is supportive with non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs for pain and beta-blockers if needed for hyperthyroid symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subacute (de Quervain\u0027s) thyroiditis typically occurs 2-8 weeks after an upper respiratory tract infection.","Key features of subacute thyroiditis include painful thyroid swelling, difficulty swallowing, and radiation of pain to jaw.","The natural history of subacute thyroiditis includes hyperthyroid, hypothyroid, and recovery phases over 6-12 months."],"references":["Desailloud R, Hober D. Viruses and thyroiditis: an update. Vir J. 2009; 6:1-14."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43711"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15277"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15277"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fa84bb32-756e-42bc-8f7c-34ae6314e53b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fa84bb32-756e-42bc-8f7c-34ae6314e53b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43711"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-30T12:13:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T12:15:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"292"}}